00:50:59.780 --> 00:51:02.180
And Stuart Haber
in the 1990s, when

00:51:02.180 --> 00:51:04.220
he started with all
this blockchain stuff

00:51:04.220 --> 00:51:06.980
and put it in the New York
Times, had a central authority.

00:51:06.980 --> 00:51:08.810
And he set up that
company Surety.

00:51:08.810 --> 00:51:11.750
And he put it in
the New York Times.

00:51:11.750 --> 00:51:15.380
And what Nakamoto consensus
is, is he said, well, no.

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:20.350
We're not going to have Haber
and a central authority.

00:51:20.350 --> 00:51:22.670
It's going to be decentralized.

00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:26.210
So these other consensus
protocols generally

00:51:26.210 --> 00:51:31.220
have some randomized approach
to delegate the selection

00:51:31.220 --> 00:51:32.540
of the next block.

00:51:32.540 --> 00:51:34.010
It's not always that way.

00:51:34.010 --> 00:51:36.470
